04314nam a22005415i 9780773551725DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735517257 a10.1515/97807735517252doi  a(DE-B1597)656068  a(OCoLC)981935048  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX4220.U6bT58 2017 7aREL0100002bisacsh04a271/.900973090452231 aTitley, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInto Silence and Servitude :bHow American Girls Became Nuns, 1945-1965 /cBrian Titley. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b6 photos, 8 tables, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v27900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figure -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tBrides of Christ … and Why So Many Were Needed -- tSeeking “Convent Material” -- tCalled or Chosen? -- tWhat If Parents Objected? -- tAspirants: Secluded from the World -- tPostulants: “Moving Backward in Time” -- tNovices: Under the Gaze of the Zelatrix -- tPostscript to 1965: Longing for the Fleshpots of Egypt? -- tConclusion -- tA Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor many American Catholics in the twentieth-century the face of the Church was a woman's face. After the Second World War, as increasing numbers of baby boomers flooded Catholic classrooms, the Church actively recruited tens of thousands of young women as teaching sisters. In Into Silence and Servitude Brian Titley delves into the experiences of young women who entered Catholic religious sisterhoods at this time. The Church favoured nuns as teachers because their wageless labour made education more affordable in what was the world's largest private school system. Focusing on the Church's recruitment methods Titley examines the idea of a religious vocation, the school settings in which nuns were recruited, and the tactics of persuasion directed at both suitable girls and their parents. The author describes how young women entered religious life and how they negotiated the sequence of convent "formation stages," each with unique challenges respecting decorum, autonomy, personal relations, work, and study. Although expulsions and withdrawals punctuated each formation stage, the number of nuns nationwide continued to grow until it reached a pinnacle in 1965, the same year that Catholic schools achieved their highest enrolment. Based on extensive archival research, memoirs, oral history, and rare Church publications, Into Silence and Servitude presents a compelling narrative that opens a window on little-known aspects of America’s convent system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConventszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGirlsxReligious lifezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355172540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773551725423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773551725/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles